# AVL & BST Tree Visualizer

An interactive full-stack Binary Search Tree (BST) and AVL Tree visualizer built from scratch to demonstrate how self-balancing trees work internally.

The core data-structure logic is implemented in C, while the visualization and interaction layer is built using JavaScript and SVG. A Python backend coordinates execution and persists operation history using SQLite.

This project was designed to deeply understand AVL rotations, balancing logic, and how low-level systems code can integrate with modern web interfaces.

---

## Features

- Interactive node insertion from the browser
- Visualization of BST and AVL trees
- Step-by-step navigation using Previous / Next buttons
- Smooth animated AVL rotations
- Color-coded rotation transitions
- Persistent backend tree state
- SQL logging of operations
- SVG-based rendering for performance and clarity

---

## Motivation

This project was built to move beyond textbook implementations of trees and focus on how they actually behave during operations. By visualizing every structural change and rotation, the internal mechanics of AVL trees become intuitive and easy to reason about.

Unlike many visualizers, the tree logic is not simulated in JavaScript. All insertions and balancing are computed in C, making this a realistic systems-level project rather than a UI-only demonstration.

